review.reviewBody: I work on my feet every day the whole day. These hikers are really, really comfortable. I got them in black and I am considering getting the green as well. I have wide feet and the toe box has more than enough room for my toes to wiggle. My feet don't slide around inside the shoe and nothing rubs. I don't tie them all the way to the top because I like sliding my feet into my shoes. They do not seem to be waterproof but I didn't buy them to be. For that the Kaha is better.
review.name: Super comfortable

review.reviewBody: One of the most important pieces of equipment I own. My Anacapas provide comfort and support. Lightweight. I'm prone to occasional plantar faciitis and these help to keep me pain free, even on moderately challenging hikes. I love these boots and highly recommend.
review.name: Best hiking boots I've ever owned

review.reviewBody: This shoe was so comfortable when I put it on, like my other Hoka shoes! I had selected this hiking model because it was advertised as waterproof. I took my dog for a walk on dewy grass, not even standing water, and my socks immediately felt wet. Unfortunately I'll have to return them, as I already have other Hoka shoes for walking on dry terrain.
review.name: Not waterproof!

review.reviewBody: I haven't been able to break them in yet but I love the color combo of the shoe! I did have to size up, normally I am a 10 but I had to get a 10.5
review.name: LOVE THE COLOR

review.reviewBody: Another happy Hoka customer. I wanted a high top shoe for the ankle support after procuring an injury. After trying on a pair in store I knew I had to size up a full shoe size for my wide feet, normal street shoe size is 8.5 Wides and I bought 9.5. These shoes are water resistant for hiking purposes so they don't breathe as much and my feet tend to run a little warmer - I live in Michigan and cooler days are on the way so this is not a issue to me. Hoka is my go-to shoe brand for comfort for work and everyday. I change out of my work hokas for my street hoka shoe.
review.name: Great Shoe size up for wide feet

review.reviewBody: I love the color and also the weight. My feet loves this style, i don't feel any pain in my feet. :D
review.name: I have been shopping Hoka Anacapa for 4 years

review.reviewBody: I got a pair of these shoes in night sky 2 months ago. Within a month, the rubber toe cap was coming loose on the inside of the right shoe. Hoka did an even exchange for another pair. (Good!) I've had the second pair for a month. Guess what is happening in the same spot on my new shoes? If you said the toe cap is coming loose in the same place you would be correct. Hoka offered a refund. (Good) And made some recommendations of other models that might work for me.(Good) But good grief!
review.name: Manufacturing flaw

review.reviewBody: At 70, I need the support of these shoes. They give me safety and comfort and stability. And, they are purple ❣️
review.name: Most excellent

review.reviewBody: Bought these for my 12 day trip around Iceland's ring road and thr golden circle. They withstood rain, snow, water, dirt, and everything in between. All of this while my feet felt warm and comfortable. Not once my feet hurt, and I walked and hiked a lot. Will definitely recommend. Just remember to size up, I usually am 8-8.5 and bought the size 9s whichi fit just right.
review.name: Great for summer hikes in Iceland

review.reviewBody: I debated sending the boots back; but ended up keeping them simply because I needed them now. They run small. They fit; but are snug & I'm glad when I get them off.
review.name: Recommend ordering 1/2 size larger

review.reviewBody: I wore these on a four night trip to the backcountry. They were incredibly comfortable and I loved the zippered pocket. By the third day, I did have to pull them up a bit but the drawstring came in handy. Our trip involved multiple water crossings and I found these tights dried quickly, which was a relief once temperatures dropped. I am 5’10” 155lbs and purchased a medium- great fit!

review.reviewBody: Just received the trek tights. I am 5’8, 127 and ordered size small. They are a bit loose and I hope they don’t stretch. Ordered the blue and garnet. Nice colors. Fit takes some adjustment.

review.reviewBody: I LOVE these! I have three colors and intend to buy the black pair: I wore them all day and barely noticed they were there. Incredibly comfortable, and they were not overly constricting. I am obsessed with these.
review.name: BEST HIKING TIGHTS!

review.reviewBody: I bought these because they were highly recommended for comfort and durability. However, no one mentioned that the seams are extremely thick and itchy. The padding around the butt is also weirdly distracting when you walk around in the tights; you can feel it shift around because it’s so much thicker than the other material. As someone who is sensory-sensitive, these were impossible to wear. Had to return them because they were so itchy, uncomfortable, and distracting. They do seem durable, but if you have issues with scratchy seams, these probably aren’t for you. They’re cute though.
review.name: Well made but not for me

review.reviewBody: I am 5'5", 130lbs with a long torso, short legs and average waist/hip/thigh measurements. Originally ordered the Abisko HD Trekking Tights in size small based on both the Fjällräven and other sizing guides. The small were so tight that I couldn't get them past my knees! So I exchanged them for size Medium which fit much better. However, I find the proportions are a bit 'off' in order to keep the reticulated patches over the knees. They are so long in the shins that extra fabric is doubled over in places, yet short in the thighs so I'm often pulling them up. Honestly, I think they're made for tall, thin and leggy Swedes! That said, the fabric feels really good (comfortable all over and rugged where it should be) and these pants are loaded with features. I love that I don't have to worry about rock scrambles or working in them. And no PFAS! *note* I tried both the Abisko Pro and the HD and prefer the HD for their more rugged build.
review.name: Technical and durable, slightly odd fit

review.reviewBody: These were my very first Fjallraven purchase and have been my hunting/scouting pants for Colorado Elk Archery for the last 5 years!  The reinforced knees and butt have been scrapped, snagged, and slid through mountains & forests and have held up incredibly well.  After 250+ days in the field I finally retired then and bought another pair.  Best investment ever.
review.name: Built tough for years of use

review.reviewBody: These were my very first Fjallraven purchase and they have been my hunting/scouting pants for Colorado Elk archery for 5 years! review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] Me son is THRILLED with this pack! He can’t wait for day hikes!
review.name: Me son is THRILLED with

review.reviewBody:
Got the stratus 36 this summer and have done a number of day hikes with it and it’s been awesome. It has all the bells and whistles of larger packs and this version without the flip lip makes it super easy to get whatever you need out of the pack. I also found it comfortable from the get go and the ventilation back works as well as it can. Thus, for day hiking, it’s a 5/5

One note I will drop is to not get this bag expecting it to be an all-around bag. I had a talon for 10 years before this guy and that pack worked decently for travel, bike commuting, hiking, and just about everything. The Stratos though is much more specialized of a pack. What I mean is I just travelled to Iceland with the stratos (which I guess the frame is actually too large for carry-on though I wasn’t stopped for it) and I found the bag too bulky and awkwardly shaped to be comfortable in the plane or in public transport. Honestly, in most urban settings it just felt cumbersome which stood out in contrast to when we were hiking and it felt perfect. Thus, if you want this for a day-hiker or maybe even a pack for a fair weather overnighter, it’s great and probably got more of what you need for that setting. If you want it to be an all-around bag, then maybe I’d point you towards the talon. Either way, very happy with it and look forward to hopefully another 10 years of hiking with it before my next Osprey daypack!
review.name: Great for intended use

review.reviewBody:
I bought an older version of this bag in 2015 so I am unsure if the quality/build is the exact same. However, I feel compelled to write this review now because it has stood the test of time and it continues to function absolutely perfectly. It is hands down one of the best purchases I've ever made. 

I am a field scientist by trade and have done a lot of traveling around the world. It lasted through several field camps, a full 2 year Peace Corps service in Zambia, multiple backpacking trips, and functioned as my school backpack. It has been to Iceland, Zambia, Namibia, South Africa, Malawi, Brazil, all around the US, and its about to join me in another backpacking trip around southern Africa. The only evidence that it has been used is all of the dirt it has accumulated over the years, and a severely cracked buckle that I accidentally broke (and the buckle STILL functions). 

I am a firm believer in cherishing your things and buying them to last. I hope Osprey still builds their bags in this way because it has become so hard to find companies that produce dependable goods without trapping you in a buying cycle. 

Here's to many more trips and field days!
review.name: Been Around the World Since 2015

review.reviewBody:
Bought these ski bibs for my teenage son who is an expert skier.  In a typical year he skis 40+ days.  After 5 days of skiing these bibs will have several rips and cuts along the inside of the ankles where your ski boots might rub together.  The fabric along the inside of the ankles is NOT DURABLE enough for a ski pant.  Everything else about these bibs are perfect... but without durable fabric at the base of the legs that is up to the challenge of ski equipment, these bibs are good for nothing more than general outdoor snow pants.  Helly Hanson has always made great products, but because neither Backcountry or HH will stand behind their warranty on this issue, I'll never buy from either again.   If you are looking for good ski bibs, spend your money on Arc'Teryx, Marmot, Patagonia or Burton.  



ibs for my son who is an expert skier.
review.name: NOT DURABLE - AVOID

review.reviewBody:
I usually hover between sizes Med and Large and ordered Large in these.  I have a bit of middle-aged spread but at 5'10-180, it ain't much.  Despite that, the torso of these bibs was way too tight and pinched when bending even slightly...and that was with no base or mid-layer on.  The legs were a smidge long, but I could have lived with those, if not for the too-tight torso.

The belt loops are too high at mid-stomach, and the back panel is some sort of soft-shell material, not the burlier fabric of the rest of the bib.

So, if you're rail-thin and of slightly above average height or more, these bibs would be perfect for you.  If you're shorter or wider, keep looking.
review.name: Tall and Thin Only

I am 6'5 so I struggle to find pants that fit in length.  I was worried a bib would cause a problem but some other reviews said they were good for tall people - they are ! Great adjustment points and the main zipper goes from your chest to where you fly would be - so no awkward bathroom breaks on the mountain.  Great design, awesome look! *Note they are a shell, no insulation (I like that best - just pointing it out) .  I would  recommend!

review.reviewBody: We bought this rack to carry my heavy E-bike it is for sure super pricy! It is definitely built well and holds the bikes well but i will saw one flaw is the key used to put the hitch on doesn't connect to the rack so you just have to remember to bring it or else you won't be getting the rack on or off the car. That was a huge bummer! I didn't think that was a good enough reason to pay the extra money for the X model. The one handed operation is seamless we love it! We were deciding between this and the Saris rack and i think we made the right decision. THe delivery was quick and easy great company as well giving the 15% off discount. Just wish we could have waited for black Friday but we needed it sooner.

review.reviewBody: Very Sturdy and Well built. Easy to use. Took me about 30 minutes to unpack and assemble. Maybe obvious to others, but install the kick lever first, as the rack will not fold and unfold without it. Once its assembled its less than one minute to get on and off your trailer hitch. less than 10 seconds to load and unload bikes. I'm glad I didn't spend the extra $300-400 on the Piston Pro X, as I'm not sure it was worth the lights that integrate into your braking system and turn signal. I have this on a Yukon, and my brake lights and turn signal on my car are much wider than the rack. Otherwise it is the same rack as the Piston Pro X in case anyone is wondering.
review.name: Very Sturdy and Well Built

review.reviewBody:
I am replacing a Thule rack of over 10 years, since it doesn't work well with modern bikes (tire size and wheel spacing). This one sits lower on my car, which means it keeps my brake and turn lights fully visible, but completely obscures my license plate. Fortunately Kuat sells a license place adapter for this very reason (~$50), to keep your car mostly street legal (without lights).
I took my bike to a mountain bike race last weekend and I couldn't imagine a better experience with hauling my bike around. It's super fast, easy to use, stable, and hinges between positions in a snap.
The only things I could give negative reviews on are arguably positive... It's very heavy, which means it's a bear to move around but solidly built. And, the lock provided is subpar, but that leaves the flexibility to get any level of lock you prefer to use. I think I'll get a heavy duty chain lock that I can just store in the trunk.
review.name: Near flawless design

review.reviewBody:
As I got an EMTB, lifting and mounting it on the roof rack (and the reverse process) became unpractical/ unsafe especially when I am spent after many miles of ups and downs. I did a lot of research on hitch mount racks and concluded that I wanted a rack with the wing style locking system and chose this Kuat Piston. 

The rack itself is fantastic as expected but man, Kuat needs some competent packaging engineers. The rack came in a pretty large cardboard box and the box did not have anything to grab for handling and carrying. I felt so sorry about an FedEx driver. It looked like the box was rolled around on the ground as its corners and edges were rounded. When I opened the box (on my driveway), I was shocked to see all the pieces were all over the place in the box. You have been warned.

Apart from that, the rack itself is robust and works great with my bike. It is heavy (~60lbs) and heavier than my bike, so it stays on my car most of the time. The bike still wiggles a bit but that is expected due to the mechanism of the wings and the fact that the bike is not one solid piece (it is. Nice to have the steering capability!). I use Velcro straps to secure each wing and wheel as an added security.

I wish they used a longer, bar-style wedge instead of the ball at the end of the hitch as the rack can still sway a bit in the receiver.
review.name: Robust product shipped in “paper bag”

review.reviewBody: Taken this on many long full-day technical rides. My full suspension bike is an XS frame with 27/5 wheels and a 130 rear fork. With my dropper fully down, my tire does contact the bag on big impacts. With that being said, this is a great bag and the seat attachment design is awesome. The bag doesn't bounce around at all. I have the smaller 0.5L size and usually fit a tube, CO2, patch kit, multi-tool, levers, zip ties, and chain lube, so I would say it holds more than I expected.
review.name: Durable, Easy to clean

review.reviewBody: I was looking for a saddle bag for my gravel bike without a seat post strap since that strap obstructs the dropper post from compressing to its full extent.  This one seems to do the trick and so far has been holding tight!
review.name: Great for dropper post!

review.reviewBody: Had this for 18 months, put it through 4500 miles of gravel riding. It's perfect. Keeps my stuff from getting wet. Easy and quick to access on the side of the road. Plenty of space but can be expanded or contracted based on how much I want to carry. A very slight looseness at the clip where it connects to the bike, which sometimes rattles a little, but it really is not noticeable anymore -- Maybe I have gotten used to it. Highly recommend!
review.name: Perfect!

review.reviewBody:
I was excited to find an option allowing me to carry spare tube, multi-tool, CO2 cartridges, snacks and such so that I could ride without a backpack.  This served that purpose, however, it does not work well on an MTB with any degree of Rear Travel on playful down hill sections.  I have experienced hitting some rollers where this product catches the rear tire and just rips right off.

This would probably work very well for rigid bikes, but I would not recommend them for those who love to ride the playful down hill on a full travel MTB.  Luckily I noticed this on some local trails quickly, and I will be selling my used Ortlieb for this reason.
review.name: Functional But...
comment:
You're kinda knocking this product where it seems like in your scenario any seat bag would do a lousy job with a mountain bike where the dropper post was all the way down and the bag may hit the rear wheel. If that's the case then no seat bag would have done a good job for you. 

I think this bag and mounting system is terrific but naturally you need to have tire clearance for it.

review.reviewBody: The Sigma has to be one of the best shoes for edges and pockets. I've never had a shoe that has been so supportive specifically in regards to powering off my big toe. While it's a stiff and supportive shoe, the back is soft giving it a bit of flexibility when smearing is needed. While I would say this shoe is meant for a very specific style of climbing/rock-type, it does have a surprising ability to function well in all-round climbing conditions.
review.name: Power Shoe

review.reviewBody: With the important caveat that I haven’t climbed with the Sigmas outside yet (something that I will remedy soon), I have really been impressed with this unique model indoors. These shoes are aggressive yet also soft and pretty comfortable. They do, however, run quite small. Think your street shoe size as a starting point. They edge very well (as advertised). Where I was pleasantly surprised was how well they smear and how they stick on awkward (angled foot placements). Along with my La Sportiva Skwamas, these will likely become my go to shoes for steeper routes.
review.name: Excellent shoe!

review.reviewBody:
I have been buying Salomon shoes for quite a while, due mainly to their fit. Unfortunately, these shoes fit like no other Salomons I have purchased. They are incredibly tight in the toe box. I would have needed to size them up a whole size to get them to fit. 
These just weren't for me.

review.reviewBody:
I am an avid trail runner, and hiker and have owned many trail shoes over the past 5-10 years. These Ultra-Flows although still new (I've had them for about a month now) have quickly become my favourite trail runners that I've ever owned. 
I primarily shop with Salomon, but have also owned trail runners from LA Sportiva and New Balance. All of these shoes have been good over the years and had their own special features that make them enjoyable, but the Ultra-Flows have quickly proven to me that they are tough, very waterproof, lightweight, and have excellent grip. I also love how they lace up rather than use the speed lace system that Salomon uses on many of it's shoes, as I have found that this breaks easily and doesn't keep the shoes tight on long runs. 
I have ran about 35km in these shoes, all around the mountains of British Columbia's West Coast, and I also use them for work as an Outdoor Ed. Teacher. They are comfortable and keep my feet dry all day, which is saying something Vancouver. 

All in all, these shoes are everything I've hoped for so far. Would recommend.
review.name: Best Trail Running Shoe I've Ever Had

review.reviewBody: Great shoes, very comfortable. The fit is very similar to Nike's. I wear an 11 in Nike and needed the 11 in these as well. They appear very well constructed and should last a long time. Would definitely buy again.

review.reviewBody:
I am primarily a gym climber so I cannot speak on using this shoe on micro foot chips. But for all disciplines of indoor climbing whether it's toe hooking, heel hooking, or smearing on volumes I would argue this is the GREATEST shoe on the market right now for the price. I climb v10 indoors in a relatively difficult gym (subjective ofc) and have had no issues using the toe edge on small foot holds or smearing. The ridiculous amount of rubber on the upper foot portion makes toe hooking on anything feel like cheating and for heel hooks you have the ribbed heel cup and additional rail that sometimes locks me in so well I get stuck when I heel hook some crimps.

I think the best part of this shoe is that it's not that arched at the midsole and rather has the forefoot arched to compensate for overhanging foot placement. As a result the arch in the forefoot makes using this shoe much more comfortable for both beginner and advanced climbers. Personally, as someone who is very flat footed this shoe is pretty comfortable even tho I downsized from a 10.5 street shoe to a 9 and would enjoy ven consider going down to 8.5.

Note: coming from the solutions comps, instinct vsr's, and tenaya oasi's this shoe gave me a much bigger boost in performance than all three.
review.name: Major UPGRADE in gym climbing

review.reviewBody: So disappointed in these. I've been wearing the mad rock sharks for 10 years. Compared to the 2.0, this new version is less sensitive and does not perch on holds well (I'm sliding a lot after several weeks of using, not a break in issue), they are more narrow, but at the same time are longer. I had to go down a half size from the 2.0 because these newer versions are made longer, but even so, it's still too long, but can't go down any more because it's too narrow. These just perform terribly, it's too bad mad rock ruined these shoes.
review.name: Terrible downgrade from shark 2.0

review.reviewBody: I love the easy one off design of the buckle system and light weight feel.  These were absolutely awesome until they broke.  The back part of the aluminum frame pulled through the plastic anchor point.  Could be a great snowshoe if all anchor points were solid.  I had about 5 miles on the shoes when they broken.  Back country.com was outstanding with customer service.
review.name: Good snowshoe, needs design change

review.reviewBody: I bought these to replace an old pair in prep for a hiking trip in the Rocky Mountains. They were super light on my feet but gave great support in deep snow even with a 30lb pack (I weigh 200lbs). The bindings were very easy to adjust while keeping my gloves on and simple to take off. Very happy with this purchase.

review.reviewBody: I can not wait to get these into powder on the mountains.  I Winter hike and i live in Alaska and I snowshow a good part of the year.  I own the 23 inches but I can not get floatation with gear which is why they tell you the wt limit is 160.  Fine if you are a smaller guy with no pack.  So this is me walking with a heavy parka, boots, clothing, insulated overpants and a daypack that weighs 4 lbs.  Your on the body gear is heavier than you think. One of my ridiculous but so warm and bear resistant Alaskan Hardgear cordura, down, coyote fur parkas wigh like 7 lbs pre humidity. Factor that all in and I had to get a 26 incher at backcountry as well.  The crampon teeth and side rail teeth (I do a lot of traversing on steeper terrain) are very aggressive and that was what I needed. Between the custom fit of the Boa, its quality and attractiveness, its design - it justifies the price easily.  I found it easier to adjust and the heel straps were of a very good quality. I have a feeling that this product may hit five stars (the 26 inch, the 23 hit 5 for casual walking around as transportation the end of last year...)These straps where the easiest to adjst on my heels. And I own a TSL, I need to take mitts off in -30F-so ease of adjstment in the trail is manditory.  These were my first Atlas's in a long while and they will not be my last.  I was impressed.
review.name: The Workmanship  (workpersonship?)

review.reviewBody:
There are some nice things about these like boa system which makes it super easy to wear. Other than that it claims to be all terrain snowshoes, unfortunately they broke on the 3rd time I used it. 

Barely used them for 10-15 miles of snowshoeing  and the rivets broke when I reached campsite. Not a reliable pair of snowshoes in the mountains. 

Also, backcountry’s warranty support isn’t as great as REI’s, it takes forever to get a response and they say I’m supposed mail the item to manufacturer coz it’s been 3 months since purchase.
review.name: Broke the third time

review.reviewBody: We?ve tried out a few different brands of snowshoes and continuously struggle with the cumbersome back strap. These Atlas Helium back straps are so much easier to manage than any others we?ve tried. Additionally, the front strap tightening mechanism is easy to use AND stays in place! No more bending over and adjusting mid-trek Highly recommend!
review.name: Fabulous product!

review.reviewBody: They work well. Very thin and light. They actually  have a toe/edge so they are a good upgrade from a beginner shoe.

I've been using this shoe in the gym and outside for a few months since my last set of climbing shoes developed a hole too big to patch. They were decently comfortable right off the bat and didn't take long to break in at all. They perform really well on overhang problems in the gym but can be used in lots of different situations. The one thing I will say is that the midsole is pretty flexible which makes standing on little footholds for long periods difficult. I'd recommend these, but especially to people who like to boulder indoors.

review.reviewBody: I wanted to love these, but I was sitting on the wet ground for less than five minutes and all the moisture soaked through! How completely disappointing.
review.name: Not actually waterproof

review.reviewBody: I got these in a size small. I’m 5’2, 26in waist and 123lbs. I was concerned about the length since I’m only 5’2 and I’ve seen reviews online that HH bibs tend to fit long, but they fit perfect! It probably has something to do with the straps because they’re super adjustable. That said, I have to agree with another review that mentioned the placement of the bib/straps were made for someone without a chest. This is not a problem for me. In fact, it’s ideal in my case, but something to consider if you’re well endowed. The only feature I wish it had is an adjustable waist. I could probably fit an XS, but I imagine the mobility would be pretty restricted and I wouldn’t be able to wear thick layers if I need to. Overall, I’m really pleased with my purchase especially at the price point! I can’t wait to test these out!
review.name: True to size!

review.reviewBody: I cannot wait to put these to use this winter. I really like how they fit. To me, the size was perfect. I am an athletic build with strong quads and glutes and not much of a waist. I got these in a medium and still have room to layer underneath-not a ton of room but adequate. I do like all the pockets and I gave them a test run in the ever-important ease of making a call to nature and they passed! I will write another review after I've used these to give my impressions on how they move and whether or not they keep me warm. But for now, I am extremely happy with them and the price point was even better!
review.name: Great Bib-hugs in all the right places

review.reviewBody: These are solid pants, rode in them twice (once on a frigid New England day) and I stayed nice and dry (and relatively warm -- it was 6º). I'm just frustrated companies don't make pants for us curvy big thighs and big butt women! I'm 5' tall with a 29 in waist, 43 in low hip, and 24 in thighs. I bought a L and they fit, but it's a struggle to zip up the thigh so I can't wear thick layers underneath. I agree with the bucket look of the bib (as I'm smaller up top) but that doesn't bother me too much, though I do wish the waist were adjustable (but it did keep the snow out). While they feel a little tight on my thighs, there is good mobility and I didn't feel restricted at all on the mountain. The length on me is hilariously long, but that's to be expected when short lengths aren't available. The bib straps are VERY stretchy, wish the straps themselves were a little shorter (because of my height), but due to their stretchiness, I was able to pee in them with all my gear on, so that's a plus!
review.name: Solid pants with some issues

review.reviewBody: I liked basically everything about these bibs except for the zipper to get them off and on. The pockets were great, the material was light, and the elastic on the bib straps was nice to get them off and on. The zipper to get them on and off was a little too far over where if I was still wearing my jacket, I couldn't zip them back up. If they redesigned the zipper 2 inches closer to the hip I think these would be amazing bibs.
review.name: Hard to get on/off with a jacket on

review.reviewBody:
I am 5'4" and 110 lbs, I ordered a size S first which was just way too big and downsized to XS and the legs and hips have plenty of room. The waist and bib part is way too big, looks like I am standing in a bucket. The waist is not adjustable. The bib and shoulder straps are also in a weird position like this was made for somebody with no chest. 
I love the material and the insulation of these pants but I will have to send it back, there is just no way to make it fit.
review.name: Too big around the waist

review.reviewBody:
For reference: I'm 5'6", 135, carry more weight in my butt and thighs (35/26/39). I ordered these in a medium and a large given the recommendation to size up. Medium fit perfectly, large was too big! 

 The zippers are easy to use, I love the pockets/pocket location, it's easy to get on and off, the legs are roomy. My only wish is that the waist could be adjustable. Otherwise I'm really happy with these and they did great on my test run!
review.name: Comfy, cozy, flexible

review.reviewBody:
I haven't used these on the mountain yet. But at 5'6 and 120 lbs and 26 inch jean size, I went with a size small. These were so tight around my rear and hips that had I not been wearing seamless underwear, you could likely see them. 

Maybe for inbound groomers, these would be ok, but the kinda movement that is required by anything more athletic.. and these won't work. I don't even have my skier bum yet and the fit is already an issue. I'm going to try a medium cause I otherwise really like them... but the length was right for small, so I don't have high hopes.

review.reviewBody: I originally bought this bag specifically for the kickstand so whenever I changed camera lenses in the woods on a hike, it wasn’t this awkward, tippy bag on the ground mess that it usually is. I’ve had this bag for probably 18 months now and I’ve used it to do that once. The kickstand is amazing but the bag when loaded and walking around is not as comfortable as my other Osprey packs. The rigid portion of the kickstand that connects to the back panel and suspension does not have enough padding when doing long hikes. It’s at the same spot that the other reviewer said pulls his shirt up. I have that happen as well but it hasn’t bothered me as much to notice. This backpack and the kickstand are far too useful for me to return this. I end up using this bag as a carryon when flying. I’ll have a 16” computer, 12” iPad, mirrorless camera, 2-3 coke can size lenses, NC over the ear headphones, battery pack and cables, and an assortment of other flying necessities. It just eats it all with space leftover for like a light jacket. Being able to set this down anywhere and grab what I want out of it without it falling over is so nice. When I don’t have to wear it for super extended amounts of time, I love this pack. I don’t personally have an issue with the water bottle holders, but it is definitely a two handed operation. I prefer this secure it holds the water bottles over the accessibility since I fly with this more than say walk around a campus with it.
review.name: A Mixed Bag

review.reviewBody:
So yeah. I don’t spend the time to write reviews often so it must be awful or amazing to get me to spend the time. 

This is amazing. 

The internal compartment can hold 2 laptops and an iPad with keyboard case. 

The water bottle sleeves are deep and hold a good bottle well. 

The front organization is nice. 

The one and only flaw of the bag is the droopy nature when it has stuff in the front organization pocket and super front pocket. Let’s get some interface or palstic ridged pipe here and this bag would earn six stars. 

Kickstand seems like something a kid would have and adults would not need, and that’s just wrong. I can not say how many times I have slung this off my shoulder into the kickstand mode and it’s just perfect as it stays upright and ready to easy deploy what I need. 

Carrying. Look if you know you know and if you don’t get it. The mesh and straps make this float as much as any ruck you’re going to carry and frankly I carry more junk than I need but I get away with it thanks to the carry system. 


I can’t speak to the water our outdoor cross over nature of this bag as I just use my mini 8 year old osprey which is still going like a tank and soiled me with again the same carriage system this has. 


Lastly I went through no less than 10 bags from various other places to arrive here at this bag. I feel like I did not settle but found home. 

Carry with care and enjoy this bag of
review.name: My everyday carry love it

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] This pack is great for an everyday work carry. The straps and back panel combo are make this the most comfortable pack I’ve ever owned. The kickstand is an awesome feature and the fabric is great. I’ve yet to be disappointed from a osprey pack to date.
review.name: This pack is great for

review.reviewBody: I've had this bag for several months now, and have taken several trips with it. I think it's pretty close to a goldilocks bag for my needs. The kickstand feature is just simply the best, I don't like floppy backpacks. It fits just fine under the seat on airplanes, unless you have it completely stuffed. The frame makes it a little long, so that on some planes it will stick out a little into where your feet are. I am 6'4", so for me getting anything out of it while on a plane is not happening with my knees in the way. The water bottle pockets are great, I had to use a taller skinnier kleen kanteen that I had, rather than the wider hydroflask, but no big deal. Water bottle pockets are always going to be a tradeoff, do you want it secure so it doesn't fall out, or do you want to be able to put a bottle back one-handed? You can't really have it both ways. For me, I want things to be secure, and these are. And if I'm traveling and have an extra day to go for a hike, plenty of room for anything you'd want to bring with, and comfortable.
review.name: Great work/travel bag

review.reviewBody: This is a mixed bag, unfortunately. In the end, I've decided to keep it, but I was really close to returning it. I think what ultimately caused me to settle was that I really appreciated how lightweight it was and how the suspension felt on my back. Here's what I didn't like: 1. It has this super annoying thing where, no matter what I'm wearing, it hikes my shirt up and exposes my lower back while I'm walking. This is because of the suspension: all of the weight of the bag sits on two points that contact my lower flanks just above my butt. As I walk, those to points rub up and down on my shirt, pulling it up but not pushing it back down. I've found that if I flip the tabs from the belt strap over to cover these points (exposing the smoother fabric on their outsides to my back, rather than the rough mesh of the back panel), it fixes the problem, but then it's uncomfortable. No winning here; I'm just hoping that eventually the fabric will wear smooth from use and the problem may go away.... 2. I strongly dislike that it only has one compression strap and it's in the middle of the back. Additionally, that one strap doesn't have the nice quick-release clips that straps usually have. If you want to adjust it - say to put your water bottle in it -, it's a two-handed operation on both sides. So not only is it annoying to adjust, but it also just pinches my bag in the middle, leaving the top and bottom to be floppy :( :(. 3. The front zippered compartment is a big pocket with a somewhat small opening. Not a huge deal, but certainly annoying. As I said, in the end, I was happy enough to keep the pack, but just barely. I think if I didn't love the Osprey brand so much I'd probably have returned it and gotten something else, but they've got me hooked.....
review.name: Delightfully lightweight, but with some annoying problems

review.reviewBody: There is a lot to like about this bag for everyday carry. I'll list out some pros and cons. Pros - Good size for carrying standard tech plus couple garments. My phone fits well in one of the admin compartment stretchy pockets. - Comfortable harness system with exceptionally breathable back panel to keep the sweat down - Stands on its own. (awesome) Cons - Stretchy fabric water bottle pockets are oddly sized, and the compression straps can prevent you from easily slotting in a bottle. I'd rather see fabric matching the exterior of the bag with hidden elastic gussets. - The kickstand becomes less stable for a bag without any weight in the bottom of the main compartment. This can cause it to topple if you have a water bottle and a laptop but not much else. - The lower part of the admin panel has no pockets. Why not use the space? - Packing out the two front pockets can restrict access to items at the bottom of the admin pocket, as they can protrude into the interior space. For example, my tech pouch will sometimes get caught up on the underside of a glasses case or power adapter in the outer pocket. - No secret pockets accessible via the side or back for passports or wallet. Conclusions: This is an attractive bag that straddles the needs of outdoor enthusiasts and everyday commuters. I recently took mine to a tech conference where its ultra-breathable back panel and ability to stand served me well. It has just enough tech organization to get me by, but I could have used more pockets in the admin panel area to have dedicated spaces for a usb power bank and charge adapters. I found the stretchy pockets made it overly difficult to slot water bottles quickly single-handed because they would get tripped up on the compression straps. Also, I found myself wanting a more hidden space for my wallet that would both make it easy to remove and not visible every time I opened the admin space. Overall, it's still a great bag.
review.name: Well-featured bag for everyday use

review.reviewBody: Terrible silicone taste that I cannot get rid of. I tried to use it today and cannot get anything out of it. Stored as per directions. review.itemreviewed: Peak Series Collapsible Squeeze 650ml Water Bottle + Filter
review.reviewBody:
I used a Lifestraw metal bottle for a year, however I travel the world for months with only a 'personsl' size bag, and metal bottle requires too much space. So I purchased Lifestraw collapsible bottle, and the tiny filter is difficult to use.
Need a big filter with collapsible bottle.
review.name: Small filter, difficult water flow

review.itemreviewed: Peak Series Collapsible Squeeze 650ml Water Bottle + Filter
review.reviewBody: This product like the larger one i purchased leaves the tap water tasting like plastic. Very disappointing.
review.name: Bad taste in my mouth

review.itemreviewed: Peak Series Collapsible Squeeze 650ml Water Bottle + Filter
review.reviewBody: I used thos a few times in situations where I ram out of water on a long run. Was very helpful. Also, it's peace of mind.
review.name: Used it in emergency situations

review.itemreviewed: Peak Series Collapsible Squeeze 650ml Water Bottle + Filter
review.reviewBody: I've owned several of these style bottle filters from a few different brands. I had high hopes for the Lifestraw version, but it has several noticeable shortcomings. First, the filter gets clogged WAY faster than the Kayadyn BeFree version. This one was filtering noticeably slower after just 2 cycles. I was filtering water from a crystal clear river in Northern WI and have filtered water from this river for years and never had this issue so soon. In order to backflush, you'll need the syringe that they send you, which can easily be lost. Because the intake on the Lifestraw filter is only on the end of it, water is only allowed to enter through a small potion of the filter....and it's the same with the backflushing. With the Kayadyn version, the filter is open 360 degrees around the filter, so a simple swooshing of the filter in the water will clean it. I must have run 10 syringes worth of water back through this thing and it's not one bit better. I've gotten approx 3 years(hundreds of bottles worth) through my Katadyn before the filter wouldn't process water any longer. My Lifestraw is almost to that point after a single 3 day trip.
review.name: There's better options out there

review.itemreviewed: Peak Series Collapsible Squeeze 650ml Water Bottle + Filter
review.reviewBody: Unless the bottle is almost completely full, it is difficult to drink by squeezing or sucking. I ended up unscrewing the top to drink, which defeats the purpose of the filter.
review.name: Squeeze bottle

review.itemreviewed: Peak Series Collapsible Squeeze 650ml Water Bottle + Filter
review.reviewBody:
Need to use it daily I use it to clean nasal rinse so the water from my doctor should be free of all chemicals and bacteria,
The squeeze bottle allows me to do this where ever I travel to.
review.name: Need to use it daily

review.itemreviewed: Peak Series Collapsible Squeeze 650ml Water Bottle + Filter
review.reviewBody: Filter is working well. Went through each step of backwashing so I can be comfortable with it. It doesn’t stand on its own but not a deal breaker. It’s more wider than I like which fits awkwardly on sides of backpack. It doesn’t fit in front pockets of running vest when bottle is full of water. But I’m still satisfied for its sole function of filtering.
review.name: I like it. It works when needed.

name: Peak Series Collapsible Squeeze 650ml Water Bottle + Filter

review.reviewBody:
Perfect size for 2 people doing car camping with mats.
Easy setup, outer shell & two doors are awesome. 
Lots of little pockets and strings to hang items on both sides of tent.

Easy to setup for one person also.
review.name: Lots of little features

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] Easy to set up, spacious, love that it has 2 doors
review.name: Awesome

review.reviewBody:
Large and spacious. Large doors in front and smaller one in back was very useful.  Coming from a smaller "4 person tent" (sierra South fork) this was more difficult to put up for one person.   Mainly because the poles are threaded through the top. This Required the tent and poles to be lifted while simultaneously bending them into place eyelets in the corners. Clips to the top might be easier to build the tent. The rainfly has a droop over the main vestibule where rain collects. No leaks observed but it makes entering during rainfall risky. We camped during a bright moon. The kiwi color made the tent seem while on the inside. Drying out took somewhat long due to some of the double over layers (zipper covers, flaps etc) trapping water. Pack size and pole design makes it just too big to be a good packing tent. Good for cars and short carry ins

Size:5/5
Set up: 4/5
Rain resistance: light rain (4/5)
Drying time: 3/5
Color option: 4/5
Wind resistance:TBD
review.name: Limestone 4p kiwi

review.reviewBody: I have been looking for a new camping tent forever. Being a bit of a penny pincher I had been burning through one cheap tent after another. I recently got the Limestone for an weekend camping trip and I love. It was rainy and windy all weekend but my tent stayed bone dry. More than that, I could actually stand in this tent and the walls being so vertical I could actually fit my wife and two kids in it without us rolling over each other all night. Even better its got these great pockets for stashing away your gear. You can tell they really thought out every aspect of this tent.
review.name: Great Tent!!!!!

review.itemreviewed: King Solomon Double Sleeping Bag: 20F Down
review.reviewBody:
We've had lots of Big Agnes gear over the years, from tents and chairs to sleeping pads. I've never looked at their sleeping systems before though. King Solomon is hands down the best sleeping solution for a couple that likes to cuddle. This is not a sleeping bag that you'd share with your friends as you'd be sleeping pretty close to each other. You can fit is over a single 40in sleeping pad or two 20-25in pads. The best thing is that it can be easily converted to a camp blanket, or even used as a single sleeping bag/quilt. 

King Solomon feels warmer than what it's rated for because there will be two of you heating the space inside. Have you ever noticed that mittens are warmer than gloves, even if they have the same thickness? Same effect is applied here. 

Unlike regular sleeping bags that have down fill all the way around you, King Solomon is more like a quilt with a hood and a sheet that wraps around your sleeping pads. You'd want to invest in a warm sleeping pad. We got Big Agnes Rapide SL Double Wide and it fits perfectly.
review.name: Best warm sleeping bag for couples

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] As an employee at Carve Designs, I have had my eye on the Jacey Dress and while I usually go for a solid color I love the Ditsy print--it has a beautiful dark green background and the colors in the flowers just pop! I bought true to size, XS (5'4"/125 lbs/34A)--if I had a larger chest I would want to size up for comfort. I love how it's got an easy fit through the body--the soft cotton fabric is soft and it's lined so this is such an easy, throw-on dress for so many occasions. I plan to pair it with a chunky cardigan or the Zella Mesh Pullover for early spring layering and will definitely have on in rotation for the summer.

They are well made and the material is great quality! I’m highly impressed with how durable these sandals are, they have held up to everyday wear and tear. I highly recommend these to anyone!

review.reviewBody:
[This review was collected as part of a promotion.] The Obama ones are incredibly comfy. They are great for going out on a warm day and are a fantastic alternative to slippers around the house. Being water proof, I can take them into the showers when I go camping, or outside when washing the car. These shoes are incredibly durable and I'll be sure to purchase a new pair once these ones wear out. I can't get 
enough of these sandals! These things offer more support than I've ever had in a sandal, and you can tell. If you wear these things all day your feet still feel good at the end of the day, also wore them around the house since they provide so much comfort!
review.name: Pure perfection!!!

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] Perfect. Excellent support if you have foot problems. I've tried many types of orthotics and these help me the most. Nice quality and they have held up extremely well.These will be your favorite sandals for everything. Very comfortable, can wear them around the house, on the beach, or heavy walking.
review.name: Best flip flops ever!!!

review.reviewBody:
[This review was collected as part of a promotion.] These are the best quality, most comfortable sandals I have ever owned. The stitching, seaming and workmanship in general is flawless. Meticulous attention to detail was given to creating this product. The wording on the top strap is embroidered and adds to the overall impression these will make. Very nice look!

The arch support on these is amazing. The padding at the heel is about the same height as the padding at the ball of the toes. This makes the sandal cradle your foot and it feels extremely natural. The toe is curled up for a smooth step, allowing the heel to rise naturally. This natural rise will help prevent the sand spray that accompanies a lot of flip-flop brands. I’m excited to see how these break in. I’m assuming they will only get more comfortable.

As far as value for the price goes, it’s hard for me to judge at this time. Based on the quality and comfort, I’m assuming I am going to own these and love these for years. I can only state that if these are in your price point, they would be an excellent choice!
review.name: Great Quality and Support

review.reviewBody:
I recently had the opportunity to try out Coleman's 8-person Skydome tent, and I must say I am quite impressed. As someone who loves camping and spending time outdoors, I am always on the lookout for high-quality camping gear that will make my adventures more enjoyable. The Skydome tent definitely delivers on that front.

One of the first things I noticed about the tent was how easy it was to set up. The pole system is color-coded, which makes it simple to figure out where each pole goes. The tent also comes with pre-attached poles, which saves time and eliminates the need to thread the poles through the tent sleeves. I was able to set up the tent by myself in under 10 minutes, which is a huge plus in my book.

The tent is also incredibly spacious, with a center height of 6 feet 5 inches. This made it easy for me and my fellow campers to move around comfortably inside the tent, even with 8 people. The vertical walls of the Skydome tent also provide plenty of headroom, which is a nice feature when you're trying to change clothes or move around inside the tent.

Another feature I appreciated about the Skydome tent was the ventilation. The tent has large windows and a mesh ceiling that allow for excellent airflow. This was especially important during the hot summer nights when I used the tent. The ventilation kept the tent cool and prevented condensation from building up inside.

The tent also comes with a rainfly, which is great for providing extra protection from the elements. The rainfly is easy to attach and does a good job of keeping the tent dry, even in heavy rain. The tent also has taped seams and welded floors, which help to keep water out and provide extra protection.

One thing I would note is that the tent does not come with a vestibule or awning, which means there is no covered area to store gear or shoes outside the tent. However, this is a minor issue, and there are aftermarket solutions available if you want to add a vestibule or awning to the tent.

Overall, I am very impressed with Coleman's 8-person Skydome tent. It is easy to set up, spacious, well-ventilated, and provides excellent protection from the elements. Whether you're camping with a large family or a group of friends, this tent is an excellent choice for your next outdoor adventure.
review.name: Excellent choice for your next outdoor adventure.

review.reviewBody: I bought the Interceptr last year and loved it so much I tried to buy another one.  I ended up getting this Aktivatr as part of that search.  I still love my Interceptr, but the Aktivatr is top notch!  The lining at the wear lines makes practical sense and as it turns out, looks good too!  I've heard that it looks "futuristic" or "Sci-Fi" from people paying compliments.  I love the thumb catch in the cuff rather than an extra strap!  Great innovation!  I'm an even bigger fan now than I was before!
review.name: Best combination of features in the line

review.reviewBody:
I liked the look/feel of the Aktivatr Mutiny Blue (S), that I then bought a second one.  These are brand new, and I like that they can be both washed and dried in a washer/dryer; whereas the Interceptr suggests line-dried only.  As they indicated, there is different levels of warmth where it seems like cool air passes more easily through some parts then others.  Not certain how I feel about that, but expect this to be a layer beneath a jacket or coat anyways.

I'm always worried about shrinking, as I'm 5'11 slim with long arms, but after a run through the wash it still fits great and the arm length of a small still reaches perfectly.
review.name: Loved this, I then bought a second one.

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] The material is thick and extremely durable. The draw string is very firm and feels like it would hold up very well. It’s not too large so taking it hiking or camping is very easy.
review.name: Very good quality

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] This is a great product for camping - super durable, lightweight, easy to use, and has enough storage for ~5 days for one person or 2 for the weekend. I feel confident in its effectiveness and will use it everytime we go camping, even if not in bear territory!
review.name: Effective and easy to use/bring!

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I haven't been camping since I received this product to test but I do have a dog. I put some food and treats in it before tying it up and putting it on the floor. She went over to it and sniffed the outside and gave it a few licks before nibbling the bag in a few spots. It held up well against her until she discovered the drawstring. Maybe it has more to do with with my knot tying abilities and that I give her treat puzzles but she was able to get into the bag in a few minutes. I'd be willing to give it a shot camping since wildlife wouldn't be as close to it as I let my dog get
review.name: Dog Resistant

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] This sack is your one stop shop. It is easily portable and you can take it where ever you want. It has drawstring’s that act as a handle and are utilized to secure the opening from being opened. The material is thick but not overly thick and it is very ridged. You can place food, clothing, medicine, basically anything you want and they come in different sizes to meet any of your needs.
review.name: This is a top quality bag

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] The Ursack Major Bear-Resistant Food Bag is an excellent choice for anyone exploring bear country or wilderness areas where food protection is crucial. Its combination of durability, lightweight design, and certified bear resistance makes it a trusted companion for outdoor adventures, providing reliable food security in challenging environments.
review.name: Resistant

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] We are a big camping family so we do a lot of backpacking and hunting and are always in need of a good bear sack, this was perfect and worked really well, loved how light weight it was and easy to carry.
review.name: Light weight

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] The packaging of the sack is nice looking. The labeling says that it is bear resistant, but that certain critters may create small holes. That would make this less useful if you were traveling in an area where mice were a problem. Like a bear bag or bear canister they do recommend that you deploy it separately away from your camp at night. they also mention other accessories like an aluminum liner to prevent crushing and puncture, as well as an odor barrier bag that they sell. My experience is that this would serve fine as a bear bag, but would not replace a bear canister. In areas where a bear bag is required, it will still be necessary to hang the bag. In an area where a bear canister is required, you might get a ticket if found using this container instead. It does say that it is certified resistant by the interagency grizzly bear committee, but this is likely not accepted by many management agencies like the national forest service or national Park service. while they do not say what the fabric blend is, it feels like it contains Kevlar to me. Closing the bear bag is simple in theory, but may be difficult for people with limited strength in their hands and or arms. I plan to use this as a heavy duty bear hang bag. It is slightly heavier than a typical nylon bag, but it would certainly hold up to abrasion better than a normal bag. ￼ I would not leave it on the ground at night. ￼
review.name: Heavy duty bear hang bag

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I was pleasantly surprised by this food sack, it’s so durable and still super light. I was especially fond of the shape of the bag which makes it great for maximizing the space.
review.name: Durable and great shape

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] Lightweight yet extremely durable alternative to traditional bear canisters. Lightweight but can hold up to 5 days worth of food for one person!
review.name: Great quality!

review.itemreviewed: Trango Tech Leather GTX Mountaineering Boot - Men's
review.reviewBody: I really really wanted to love these boots but they didn't fit my foot very well. I wear size 11M US in most  footwear types. Running shoes up half a size.  I knew boots can be tricky to size sometimes so I ordered 44.5 and 45. The 45 was too loose to when i had it cinched down, my foot was sliding around enough to make me concerned for blisters on a long outing. The 44.5’s were too narrow in the toe box, pinching off circulation too much for me. Outside of fit, these boots seemed like a great price point for a hybrid backpacking/summer mountaineering boot. They definitely felt secure and stiff underfoot. I just wish they fit me better.
review.name: Sizing Funky

review.itemreviewed: Trango Tech Leather GTX Mountaineering Boot - Men's
review.reviewBody:
I bought these for my first mountaineering boots and they have performed well in relatively mild conditions.  The boots have enough flex that there is no issues using them on decently long approaches, but are still stiff enough to perform on steep snow and short scrambles.  They kept my feet toasty on chilly days but my toes began to get pretty cold when the temp dropped to around 10F one evening hiking into camp at about 12,500 ft.

All in all, great boot if you are looking for an affordable option to try the sport out or if you plan on sticking to well established routes in the lower 48 during early spring/late fall.  If you plan to cross a glacier, you may want to look for a sturdier boot.
review.name: Great boots but wont handle everything

review.itemreviewed: Trango Tech Leather GTX Mountaineering Boot - Men's
review.reviewBody: I use this for crushing 14er's. My feet used to ache so much before I got a pair of these much stiffer boots. They flex plenty in the midfoot for the approach and support whatever weight I need to carry with ease. The lacing system and fit is ideal for my wider foot, as a Mens US 10.5 I found the European 45's to be perfect.
review.name: Lighter and faster than other Mountaineering Boots

review.reviewBody: I've had my eye on this ActiveIce sun shirt here on OR. When I saw it on sale I decided to get it. I'm glad I did! It is super comfortable. The large fits my 6' slender frame just right and the sleve length is perfect for me. The shirt is stretchy and does dry quickly. review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] As an avid hiker and outdoor enthusiast, I recently purchased the ActiveIce Spectrum Sun LS in Titanium, and I must say, it's been a game-changer. The color was exactly as depicted in the photos, and the material looks just as impressive in person. I put it to the test during hikes and outdoor work under the scorching sun, and it did not disappoint. The breathability and durability of this shirt are outstanding. I accidentally snagged it on a pallet, but thanks to its stretchiness, it survived without a tear-a real lifesaver. What iDelmpressed me the most is how it doesn't cling to my skin, providing much-needed freedom of movement during those hot and sweaty days. Being someone with a darker complexion, sun protection is paramount for me. The ActiveIce Spectrum Sun LS excels in this department, effectively blocking the sun's rays and keeping me comfortable during extended outdoor activities. If I had to mention one minor quibble, it would be the fit. As a 5'11" individual weighing 154 lbs, I found it to be a bit too relaxed. I wish it were more fitted to complement my physique better. Overall, I can confidently say that this purchase was solid. The ActiveIce Spectrum Sun LS has become my go-to outdoor companion, and I'm already considering getting more. Whether it's hiking or working in the sun, this shirt has proven itself to be a reliable and comfortable asset to have.
review.name: A Cool Companion for Adventure

review.reviewBody:
I just came back from 14 days in the Beartooth mountains. This tent performed very well. Weathered extreme winds (the highest I have ever camped in), driving rain, sleet, and snow (7-8”). It was a rock. The only reason that this is not a 5 star review is that you need 4 to 6 additional guy lines & pegs to make this thing bulletproof but they do not come with the tent when you purchase it. My recommendation to anybody who is buying these Access tents is to buy the additional guy lines and pegs… once you add them this thing is unstoppable. 
I did read comments about condensation issues but I did not experience any more or less condensation using this tent. Condensation happens in cold weather camping & you just need to manage it.
review.name: A Rock of a Tent

review.reviewBody: I got a wrong pole I think which is access 3p pole and it is take me a lot of time to get the thing right.
review.name: Wrong tent pole

review.reviewBody: Loving this tent so far! It's super lightweight, has double entry with sizeable vestibule space, is easy to pack, and the stuff sack makes an excellent pillow (after adding your extra clothes of course).
review.name: My new favorite!

review.reviewBody:
-a lot of condensation
-the pole broke after one season of use and can't be fixed
-so many strings
review.name: I don't love it

review.reviewBody: Has MSR done anything to address the innumerable issues owners have had with the poles? I really want to love this tent but every review forum I can find there are a slew of owners who have noted the plastic pole inserts breaking or the pole ends splitting from modest use. No doubt the Syclone material is great stuff in terms of the mid section of the poles but if the plastic inserts are breaking and/or the Syclone material is prone to delaminating at the pole ends where the inserts reside then something simply has to be done I'd think?? Any changes in the works to address this??
review.name: What about the poles?

review.reviewBody:
I have the original version of this tent. Bought this tent for ski traverses as this tent is intended for. It works alright in a windy fall alpine environment, but when there is little wind or the temperature is much below zero degrees C there are many condensation issues. This tent provides an excellent lesson in the water cycle to any mountaineers who care to use it in winter conditions. Also had the poles break on my second trip out with this due to poor construction and weak pole material. Though I got replacement parts, I would be very hesitant to take this tent on any serious expedition. There are more robust lightweight options out there. 

This tent could be greatly improved by providing poles that can stand up to winter conditions and providing roof and fly venting to better manage condensation. I have two TNF winter tents that manage condensation exceedingly well with their vents.
review.name: Light, Condensation Issues, Bad Poles

review.reviewBody: I was extremely excited to use this tent. After a couple of camping trips I really liked it. However when I took it into colder temperatures one of the plastic pole tips broke, with little stress put on it. Makes you wonder why they put plastic pole tips on a 4-season tent. After sending my poles in and waiting for a couple months they were sent back and they were said to be fixed but nothing was changed and the tip was still broken. I wanted to love this tent, it is beautiful and well made but the poles and Cascade Designs (parent company) service is terrible. Especially for this tent costing what it does.
review.name: Bad poles and worse service.

review.reviewBody: I recently used this tent in the summer and it did not get as hot inside as other tents I have used, which was very nice. It also withstood heavy rain without anything in the tent or vestibule getting wet. The size is perfect for one person if you need space to put your stuff. The tent was very easy and quick to pitch, but folding the poles back up was a bit tedious.
review.name: Great for summer, looking forward to winter!

review.reviewBody: One tent that does everything - really. Short of full-blown exposed mountaineering conditions, this tent is about the perfect all season tent. Condensation has never been an issue for me with this tent. Pay attention to the relative humidity, what you're pitching on, vent high and low - adjust your fly tension and just make sure air is getting in and venting out. Spend enough time in the outdoors with your tent and you'll figure it out. This is a great tent that bridges the gap between backpacking and mountaineering tents.
review.name: Quiver of One!

review.reviewBody: As a full-time mountain guide for Colorado Mountain School I have spent years guiding and camping in many different environments and feel pretty savvy with pitching a tent. When I read the description of the MSR Access 2 tent stating that it is easy to set up I figured the best test was to have someone who has never camped before attempt the process of pitching the tent. My client from Italy had not only ever camped but had never even seen a tent before our camping 101 class. I gave him the tent without any instructions how to proceed, but he managed to put the tent up without any difficulties and kept saying ""this is easy"". It helps that the stuff sack has very clear pictures depicting the process. Mission accomplished! For my client's first night sleeping in a tent I let him explore the luxury of sleeping solo in there. He was so very pleased with how lightweight and packable the tent was and the comfort and roomie feeling inside that he is looking to get one for himself even if it is considered a two-person tent. It was fairly warm during our camping experience and in the desert heat it did ventilate sufficiently but not great. The mesh vents are pretty small but camping without the fly would be the preferred option when in warmer temperatures. The next testing environment was at 11,000 feet in the Gore Range in Colorado, where I was teaching a beginning mountaineering course. The inside of the tent is very comfortable for two but there is not much extra room inside for gear storage. This is not of great concern as there are two vestibules that are large enough for backpack storage and for cooking.There are two mesh pockets inside the tent big enough for storing small items (phone, headlamp, lip balm etc.) but they are not quite big enough for larger items such as socks and gloves. The tent is fine for two people sleeping head to foot but the sidewalls are not that steep so the tent body tends to hit the sleeping bags.
review.name: Excellent lightweight tent

review.reviewBody:
This is a great size bag for me to take to work!

Gregory…does your design team remember what a Nalgene is? The water bottle pockets are so tight and small on this bag, that it is darn near impossible to keep a Nalgene bottle in there without it popping out…and that’s if I can even get the bottle in the pocket when the bag has a few items in it.

I’ve made the same comment about the Nano 20.

When did the regular Nalgene 1L bottle fall out of favor as the industry standard?

Is the idea to cater to the crowd that seems to favor dainty half liter bottles?

One of the water bottle pockets is already starting to rip because it takes so much effort to try to get the Nalgene in there.

Yes, I absolutely have to carabiner the bottles to the bag, and it’s not uncommon for those bottles to pop out and sway back and forth as I’m walking…and that’s just going from the parking lot into work.

Really Gregory, if you’d just run this by me before making a whole product line with these inadequate, just for show water bottle pockets, I would have demonstrated how epically the fail every single day and suggest strongly that you tweak the design before shipping these out.

I’m happy to field test things like this so you don’t end up spending so much time on repairs when these fail…and they will fail quickly.

Let me know. I’m here to help!
review.name: Do designers remember the Nalgene?

review.reviewBody: Got this pack to take on short hikes with my dog. It is small yet adequate to fit all the things I need. Water for me and the pup, rain gear, an extra layer and hat, emergency bivy/shelter, first aid kit, snacks and plenty of room to spare. The east access is great for your keys, snacks, lip balm etc. I love the clips on the front to hang my flashlight, clip a hat, or even hold my long leash. The fit is extremely comfortable and the chest strap is adjustable to height as well as width for a very custom fit. Took a risk ordering this online without trying it on but I’m so glad I did.
review.name: Comfortable, functional and stylish

review.reviewBody: Great size for day hiking.  Well-made, pretty color.
review.name: Nice pack

review.reviewBody: Great bag, and fits well! I have many plans for this backpack. It is lightweight, fits comfortably, and is adjustable in all the right places for my body.
review.name: Love this backpack!

review.reviewBody:
Great pack for us larger people. I think I’m somewhere between this size an a regular size, hence the 4 stars. It’s a tad too big in the shoulder vee and straps.
I’m 5’8” and 185 pounds. But mostly I’m heavy and have medium size bones. This pack is perfect when I’ve got all my winter garb on and am heading out. Very nice quality and perfect capacity for 1-3 hours.
review.name: Nice pack, appreciate the plus size.

review.reviewBody: Being a plus size woman, I appreciate Gregory taking the time, effort, research, and to create this option. Fits comfortably.
review.name: Thank you Gregory!
comment: We are so happy to be part of your adventures!

review.reviewBody: This is a really nice pack and I bet for a plus size guy this would work well but as a plus size women this pack was very big in the shoulders and a little too long in the body for my 5’3 frame.
review.name: Nice pack with size issues

review.reviewBody: When Gregory announced their plus-sized line, I was cautiously optimistic. So many companies advertise plus-sized outdoor gear/clothing but don't actually resize the items. Instead they add some extra inches of webbing or extensions you can purchase separately. Gregory completely revamped their packs and made every part of them plus-sized, not just the straps. I finally have a pack that fits my body, and doesn't leave sore spots and rubbed raw skin after a hard day of hiking. I've carried this pack on trails and through towns/cities for a year and it hasn't failed to meet and exceed every expectation/test I put it to. Their iconic durability and usability now in a pack made specifically for plus-sized bodies. Thank you Gregory for helping bring inclusivity to the outdoors!
review.name: A pack that fits my body!

review.reviewBody: This is a great bag for everyday use, hiking and concerts! Perfect bag!
review.name: Great bag

review.reviewBody: This is the perfect sized bag for running around town! It is light weight and stylist. The straps fit so well and there is more space inside than it seems. Even my bike helmet fit inside! Thank you for making these plus sized packs!!
review.name: Perfect for around town errands.
